08055nam a22010935i 9783839446416DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97838394464167 a10.14361/97838394464162doi  a(DE-B1597)508138  a(OCoLC)1083571840  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041102bisacsh00aStanislaw Brzozowski and the Migration of Ideas :bTransnational Perspectives on the Intellectual Field in Twentieth-Century Poland and Beyond /ced. by Edward M. Swiderski, Jens Herlth. 1aBielefeld : btranscript Verlag, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (362 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLettre00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tOn Brzozowski's Presence and Absence in Poland and Beyond -- tTRANSNATIONAL PERSPECTIVES -- t"Sounding out idols": Brzozowski and Strindberg as Nietzsche Readers -- t"Ibsen! Oh, let us not invoke this name in vain!" Brzozowski's Ibsen Not-quite-read -- tStanisław Brzozowski and Die Neue Zeit -- tLes Déracinés: Brzozowski and Barrès -- tThe Cult of Will and Power: Did Brzozowski Inspire Ukrainian Nationalism? -- tBrzozowski and Cioran: The Legend of Young Poland and The Transformation of Romania -- tBrzozowski and the Italians -- tBrzozowski and Rorty: Coping with the Contingent Self -- tBRZOZOWSKI'S PRESENCE IN TWENTIETH-CENTURY LITERARY CRITICISM AND THEORY -- tStanisław Brzozowski and Romantic Revision (Meyer Howard Abrams, Northrop Frye, Harold Bloom): Prolegomena -- tBrzozowski as Precursor to Contemporary Studies on Cyprian Norwid's Legacy -- tBrzozowskianism: The Trouble with the "Great" Brzozowski and His Followers -- t"...actually speaking, this man converted me": Jerzy Liebert, Brzozowski, and the Question of a Modern Religous Poetry -- tStanisław Brzozowski as Harbinger and Enabler of Modern Literary Theory in Poland and the West -- tThe Stalinist Reception of Stanisław Brzozowski's Philosophy: The Case of Paweł Hoffman -- tBrzozowski and the Question of Engagement: On a Different Concept of the Autonomy of Art -- tBrzozowski or Plots of the Future -- tEpilogue -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAs a writer, critic, and philosopher, Stanisław Brzozowski (1878-1911) left a lasting imprint on Polish culture. He absorbed virtually all topical intellectual trends of his time, adapting them for the needs of what he saw as his primary mission: the modernization of Polish culture. The essays of the volume reassess and contextualize Brzozowski's writings from a distinctly transnational vantage point. They shed light on often surprising and hitherto underrated affinities between Brzozowski and intellectual figures and movements in Eastern and Western Europe. Furthermore, they explore the presence of his ideas in twentieth-century century literary criticism and theory.  afunded by Swiss National Science Foundation (SNSF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 4aCultural History. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEastern European History. 4aLiterary Criticism In 20th Century Poland. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterary Theory. 4aLiterature. 4aPolish Intellectual History. 4aSlavic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Eastern (see also Russian & Former Soviet Union).2bisacsh  aCultural History.  aCultural Studies.  aEastern European History.  aLiterary Criticism In 20th Century Poland.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterary Theory.  aLiterature.  aPolish Intellectual History.  aSlavic Studies.1 aBalbierz, Jan, econtribu